{
  "schema_version": 3,
  "id": "topology-phd-2022-aug",
  "subject": "PhD Topology",
  "subject_tag": "topology-phd",
  "year": 2022,
  "month": "august",
  "part": null,
  "pdf_url": "https://gma.math.ufl.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/130/PhD-Topology-2022_08.pdf",
  "content": [
    {
      "type": "instructions",
      "text": "Work the following problems and show all work. Support all statements to the best of your ability."
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Suppose \\(M\\) is a compact 5-manifold with \\(H_0(M;\\mathbb{Z})=\\mathbb{Z}\\), \\(H_1(M;\\mathbb{Z})=\\mathbb{Z}_3\\), and \\(H_2(M;\\mathbb{Z})=\\mathbb{Z}\\). Is \\(M\\) orientable? What are \\(H_3(M;\\mathbb{Z})\\), \\(H_4(M;\\mathbb{Z})\\), and \\(H_5(M;\\mathbb{Z})\\)?"
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Let \\(M\\) be a compact, connected, nonorientable 3-manifold. Prove that \\(H_1(M;\\mathbb{Z})\\) is infinite."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Let \\(X\\) be a connected metric space with metric \\(d\\) and let \\(p\\in X\\). Prove that if \\(X\\setminus\\{p\\}\\ne\\varnothing\\), then \\(X\\setminus\\{p\\}\\) is not compact."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Let \\(\\Sigma_g\\) denote the closed surface of genus \\(g\\), and let \\(\\Sigma_{g,r}\\) denote the surface of genus \\(g\\) with \\(r\\) boundary components (i.e., \\(\\Sigma_g\\) with \\(r\\) discs removed). Which of the surfaces \\(\\Sigma_{g,r}\\) can admit a map \\(f:\\Sigma_{g,r}\\to\\Sigma_{g,r}\\) homotopic to the identity that does not have a fixed point?"
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Let \\(X\\) be the space obtained by filling in two discs in the torus, as shown (the discs lie inside the surface of the torus). Compute \\(H_\\bullet(X;\\mathbb{Z})\\)."
          },
          {
            "type": "tikz",
            "id": "filled-torus",
            "alt": "Diagram of a torus shown as a flattened oval with a small central opening. Two black-outlined, diagonally hatched disks fill openings on the left and right sides of the torus.",
            "libraries": [],
            "options": [
              "line cap=round",
              "line join=round",
              "x=1cm",
              "y=1cm"
            ],
            "code": "% Left filling disc\n\\fill[black!20]\n    (-4.4,0)\n    .. controls (-3.65,0.85) and (-2.10,1.25) .. (-1.05,0.15)\n    .. controls (-1.75,-0.75) and (-3.45,-0.80) .. cycle;\n\n\\begin{scope}\n    \\clip\n        (-4.4,0)\n        .. controls (-3.65,0.85) and (-2.10,1.25) .. (-1.05,0.15)\n        .. controls (-1.75,-0.75) and (-3.45,-0.80) .. cycle;\n    \\foreach \\x in {-4.7,-4.3,-3.9,-3.5,-3.1,-2.7,-2.3,-1.9,-1.5,-1.1}\n        \\draw[line width=0.45pt]\n            (\\x,-1.05) -- ++(0.62,2.15);\n\\end{scope}\n\n\\draw[line width=1pt]\n    (-4.4,0)\n    .. controls (-3.65,0.85) and (-2.10,1.25) .. (-1.05,0.15)\n    .. controls (-1.75,-0.75) and (-3.45,-0.80) .. cycle;\n\n% Right filling disc\n\\fill[black!20]\n    (1.15,0.15)\n    .. controls (2.15,1.05) and (3.75,1.15) .. (4.4,0)\n    .. controls (3.95,-0.85) and (2.15,-0.80) .. cycle;\n\n\\begin{scope}\n    \\clip\n        (1.15,0.15)\n        .. controls (2.15,1.05) and (3.75,1.15) .. (4.4,0)\n        .. controls (3.95,-0.85) and (2.15,-0.80) .. cycle;\n    \\foreach \\x in {0.9,1.3,1.7,2.1,2.5,2.9,3.3,3.7,4.1}\n        \\draw[line width=0.45pt]\n            (\\x,-1.05) -- ++(0.62,2.15);\n\\end{scope}\n\n\\draw[line width=1pt]\n    (1.15,0.15)\n    .. controls (2.15,1.05) and (3.75,1.15) .. (4.4,0)\n    .. controls (3.95,-0.85) and (2.15,-0.80) .. cycle;\n\n% Outer boundary of the torus\n\\draw[line width=1.2pt]\n    (-4.4,0)\n    .. controls (-4.45,1.65) and (-2.25,2.45) .. (0,2.40)\n    .. controls (2.40,2.38) and (4.20,1.65) .. (4.4,0);\n\n\\draw[line width=1.2pt]\n    (4.4,0)\n    .. controls (4.15,-1.10) and (2.25,-1.45) .. (0,-1.35)\n    .. controls (-2.45,-1.48) and (-4.25,-1.05) .. (-4.4,0);\n\n% Central hole\n\\draw[line width=1.15pt]\n    (-1.05,0.15)\n    .. controls (-0.55,0.72) and (0.65,0.72) .. (1.15,0.15)\n    .. controls (0.62,-0.48) and (-0.55,-0.48) .. cycle;"
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "instructions",
      "text": "Answer the following with complete definitions, statements, or short proofs."
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prove or give a counterexample: If \\(A\\subset X\\) is path-connected, then the closure \\(\\overline{A}\\) is path-connected."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Compute \\(\\chi(\\mathbb{R}P^2\\times\\mathbb{C}P^3\\times S^4)\\)."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Give the definition of a normal topological space. Show that a smooth manifold is a normal space."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prove that a continuous bijection from a compact space to a Hausdorff space is a homeomorphism."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prove that if \\(m\\ne n\\), then \\(\\mathbb{R}^m\\) is not homeomorphic to \\(\\mathbb{R}^n\\)."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prove that the torus \\(T^2=S^1\\times S^1\\) is not homotopy equivalent to \\(S^1\\vee S^1\\vee S^2\\)."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "State the Tietze Extension Theorem."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Describe all the connected covering spaces \\(E\\to\\mathbb{R}P^2\\vee\\mathbb{R}P^3\\)."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Does the following exact sequence of abelian groups necessarily split? Prove or give a counterexample.\n\\[0\\to\\mathbb{Z}_2\\to A\\to\\mathbb{Z}_2\\to 0\\]"
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "problem",
      "problem": {
        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Compute the integral homology of the space \\(\\mathbb{C}P^2\\times\\mathbb{R}P^2\\)."
          }
        ],
        "subparts": []
      }
    }
  ]
}
